  {
    "client_msg_id": "aa696f50-57be-46b7-8bb7-51b803cf2d1f",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "Hi, I'm Duncan,\n\nI'm building <https://thorny.io>, an interactive notebook for decision making.\nI want to help engineers tackle overwhelming design, planning and strategy problems where multiple decisions are tangled together.\n\nThe end goal is not a programming tool but it is still an end-user computation problem because at their most general level, decisions, plans and reasoning, are actually types of computation.\n\nThe underlying structure is a knowledge graph which includes possibilities and reasoning (similar to syntax tree).\nLike a spreadsheet, if you change the reasoning, decisions or beliefs, then the consequences ripple through the graph.\nThe UI I have been exploring is\n- an outliner (effectively a structure editor for a reasoning notation)\n- with spreadsheet power (it supports formulas that reference other parts of the knowledge graph)\nThe demos on the site are out of date and baffling, I will update them with the current version shortly!\n\nI am based in Bristol UK. I studied CompSci at Cambridge and was previously head of software at an engineering firm building various design and optimization tools for engineers. I am interested in the typical Brett Victor topics plus:\n- non-monotonic reasoning\n- belief networks\n- logic programming\n- argument mapping\n- optimization and solvers\n\nI have also built various compilers, code generation and visualization tools.\nI want to work more in the open and share more but I find it tough.\nI am so impressed with <@U5TCAFTD3> and this community, I have so much to learn here!",
